{{Location map |Pacific Ocean |relief=1 |label=Ontong Java Plateau |lon_dir=E |lat_dir=S |lat_deg=3|lat_min=3 |lon_deg=160|lon_min=23 |position=right |width=300 |float=right |mark=Cercle rouge 100%.svg |marksize=20 |caption=Location of the Ontong Java Plateau in the Pacific Ocean }} The '''Ontong Java Plateau''' ('''OJP''') is a huge [[oceanic plateau]] located in the south-west [[Pacific Ocean]], north of the [[Solomon Islands]]. The OJP was emplaced {{Circa}} 120&nbsp;Ma with a much smaller volcanic event {{Circa}} 90&nbsp;Ma. Two other south-west Pacific plateaus, [[Manihiki Plateau|Manihiki]] and [[Hikurangi Plateau|Hikurangi]], now separated from the OJP by [[Cretaceous]] [[ocean basin]]s, are of similar age and composition and probably formed as a single plateau and a contiguous [[large igneous province]] together with the OJP.<ref>{{Harvnb|Taylor|2006|loc=Abstract}}</ref> When emplaced this Ontong Java-Manihiki-Hikurangi plateau covered 1% of Earth's surface and represented a volume of {{Convert|80000000|km3|abbr=on}} of [[basalt]]ic [[magma]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Rizo|2016}}</ref> This "Ontong Java event", first proposed in 1991, represents the largest volcanic event of the past 200 million years, with a magma emplacement rate estimated at up to {{Convert|22|km3|abbr=on}}/year over three million years, several times larger than the [[Deccan Traps]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Tarduno|Mayer|Winterer|Sliter|1991|p=401}}</ref> The smooth surface of the OJP is punctuated by [[seamount]]s such as the [[Ontong Java Atoll]], the largest atoll in the world.<ref name="Neal">{{Harvnb|Neal|Mahoney|Kroenke|Duncan|1993|loc=Physical features and gross structure of the OJP, pp. 184–187}}</ref>
==Geological setting== The OJP covers {{Convert|1,500,000|km2|abbr=on}}, roughly the size of Alaska. It reaches up to {{Convert|1700|m|abbr=on}} below sea level but has an average depth closer to {{Convert|2|-|3|km|abbr=on}}. It is bounded by Lyra Basin to the north-west, East Mariana Basin to the north, Nauru Basin to the north-east, and the Ellice Basin to the south-east. The OJP has collided with the Solomon Islands island arc and now lies on the inactive [[Vitiaz Trench]] and the [[Pacific Plate|Pacific]]-[[Australian Plate|Australian]] plate boundary.<ref name="Neal" />
The high plateau, with a crustal thickness estimated to at least {{Convert|25|km|abbr=on}} but probably closer to {{Convert|36|km|abbr=on}}, has a volume of more than {{Convert|5000000|km3|abbr=on}}. The maximum extent of the event can, however, be much larger since lavas in several surrounding basins are closely related to the OJP event and probably represent dike swarms associated with the emplacement of the OJP.<ref name="Neal" />
==Tectonic evolution== OJP formed quickly over a [[mantle plume]] head, most likely the then newly formed [[Louisville hotspot]], followed by limited volcanism for at least 30 million years. The extant seamounts of the [[Louisville Ridge]] started to form 70&nbsp;Ma and have a different [[Isotope|isotopic]] composition, and therefore a shift in intensity and magma supply in the plume must have occurred before that.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mahoney|Storey|Duncan|Spencer|1993|loc=Abstract}}</ref>
The early, short-duration eruptions of OJP coincide with the global [[Anoxic event#Jurassic and Cretaceous|Early Aptian oceanic anoxic event]] (known as OAE1a or the Selli Event, 125.0–124.6&nbsp;Ma) that lead to the deposition of black [[shale]]s during the interval 124–122&nbsp;Ma. Additionally, isotopic records of seawater in sediments have been associated with the 90&nbsp;Ma OJP submarine eruptions.<ref>{{Harvnb|Tejada|Suzuki|Kuroda|Coccioni|2009|loc=Abstract; Introduction, pp. 855–856}}</ref>
About 80% of the OJP is being [[Subduction|subducted]] beneath the Solomon Islands. Only the uppermost 7&nbsp;km of the crust is preserved on the Australian Plate.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mann|Taira|2004|loc=Abstract}}</ref> This collision has [[Tectonic uplift|lifted]] some of the OJP between {{Convert|200|-|2000|m|abbr=on}} above sea level. The construction of Pliocene stratovolcanoes in the western end of the convergence zone has resulted in the [[New Georgia Islands]] ({{Convert|1768|m|abbr=on}}) and [[Bougainville Island]] ({{Convert|2743|m|abbr=on}}). Shortening, uplift, and erosion of the northern Melanesian arc and the Malaita [[accretionary prism]] at deep levels has produced [[Guadacanal]] ({{Convert|2447|m|abbr=on}}), [[Makira]] ({{Convert|1250|m|abbr=on}}), and [[Malaita]] ({{Convert|1251|m|abbr=on}}).<ref>{{Harvnb|Mann|Taira|2004|loc=Erosional levels of rocks in the Solomon Islands, p. 166}}</ref>
